      <field name="fulltext">AN INFANT ABOLITIONIST. How often by a sinless child May we of error be beguiled; How oft a single, simple word The sealed springs of thought have stirr'd, And waken'd feelings deep, to be A lesson for futurity! The gayest, most aerial thing, That moves on earth without a wing, Today such lesson taught to me. How sweetly, yet unconsciously, The infant maiden, artless, mild, Reproved her elder playmate's pride! And yet the babe has only smiled Three years by her fond mother's side. They stood before a pictureâone Where dark 'neath Afric's burning sun, A wild and lonely native lay: The child's companion turn'd to say, âThere 's an old nigger, Anne, see!â And pointed to the African; The little one said quietly, âI see he is a colored man.â Ah, well may sages bow to thee, Loving and guileless infancy! And sigh, amid their learned lore, For one untaught delight of thineâ And feel they 'd give their wisdom's store To know again thy truth divine! The boasted power of eloquence Can sway the soul with magic artâ But simple words from innocence May sink more deeply in the heart.</field>
